<bill id="DLM2290000" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2009" bill.no="245" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2008">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Trade Marks (International Treaties and Enforcement) Amendment Bill</title>
    <billtype xml:lang="en-NZ">Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Foreign Affairs, Defence and Trade Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM2353600" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="245" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2008">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Foreign Affairs, Defence and Trade Committee has examined the Trade Marks (International Treaties and Enforcement) Amendment Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Trade Marks (International Treaties and Enforcement) Amendment Bill is an omnibus bill to amend the Trade Marks Act 2002 and the Copyright Act 1994. The bill aims to give effect to the Government’s decisions to ratify the Singapore Treaty on the Law of Trade Marks, and to accede to the Nice Agreement Concerning the International Classification of Goods and Services for the purposes of the Registration of Marks, and the Madrid Protocol Relating to the Madrid Agreement. It also seeks to strengthen the existing enforcement provisions in the Trade Marks Act and the Copyright Act to deter counterfeiting of registered trade marks and piracy of copyright-protected works. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Our commentary on the bill addresses only the more significant amendments. It does not cover any minor or technical amendments.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Commencement clause</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Clause 2(2) provides for 10 clauses in the bill to be brought into force by the Governor-General by Orders in Council. These clauses concern the registration of titles to trade marks, the appointment and powers of enforcement officers and Customs officers, compliance with the Singapore Treaty, and the implementation of the Madrid Protocol in New Zealand. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We were told that the provision for commencement by Order in Council for these clauses was to allow for regulations to be made on a range of matters, from merely procedural matters to extensive and complex technical regulations to implement the Madrid Protocol. The implementation of the Madrid Protocol would involve the International Bureau of the World Intellectual Property Organization; the Intellectual Property Office of New Zealand would have to coordinate with the International Bureau concerning the implementation of the Madrid system in New Zealand. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We accept that these are valid reasons for commencement by Order in Council and urge the Ministry of Economic Development to implement all aspects of the legislation expeditiously. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>However, we are concerned that the explanatory note to the bill did not adequately explain the reasons for the 10 clauses that were to be brought into force by Order in Council. We urge the Ministry of Economic Development to ensure that, in future, an explanatory note has sufficient information to enable a select committee to make a judgement as to whether commencement provisions by Order in Council are justified.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We will monitor commencement of this legislation and invite the Minister to report to the Foreign Affairs, Defence and Trade Committee in the event that not all clauses in the legislation have fully commenced within two years, for the purpose of explaining why not.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Regulation-making powers </heading>
        <para>
          <text>Clause 25 inserts new section 199A, which provides for regulation-making powers to give effect to the Madrid Protocol. We were told that clause 25 is based on similar legislation implemented in other jurisdictions and provides for the operational implementation of the Madrid Protocol. We were assured that the purpose of clause 25 is to allow effect to be given to the Madrid Protocol, and not to amend the primary legislation by regulation. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We sought clarification regarding new section 199A(h), which would allow regulations to be made to provide for the application of certain provisions of the principal Act concerning the protection and enforcement of registered trade marks “to a protected international trademark (New Zealand)”.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We understand that under the Madrid Protocol international trade mark registrations for which the Commissioner does not refuse protection are referred to in the bill as “protected international trade marks (New Zealand)”, and in accordance with New Zealand’s obligations under the Madrid Protocol will have the same rights and remedies as a registered trade mark in New Zealand. New section 199A(h) specifies the provisions governing the protection of registered trade marks that are relevant to achieving this purpose and which may be applied by regulation to protected international trade marks (New Zealand) under the Trade Marks Act. We are satisfied that the purpose and intended effect of new section 199A(h) is to provide international trade marks (New Zealand) with the same protection as New Zealand-registered trade marks. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Additional power for enforcement officers</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Clause 17 provides for the appointment of enforcement officers under the Trade Marks Act 2002, and clause 31 provides for the appointment of enforcement officers under the Copyright Act 1994.  </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending clauses 17 and 31 to insert new section 134WA to 134WD. These new sections provide for additional investigative powers for enforcement officers. Among other things, they would allow enforcement officers to apply for a production order where they suspected on reasonable grounds that a person had documents that were evidence of, or might be of significant relevance to, an investigation of an offence against any specified sections of the Trade Marks Act or of the Copyright Act; the issuing of a production order by a District Court judge; the powers of an enforcement officer in respect of documents required to be produced under a production order, and the penalties for failure to comply with a production order. Our recommended amendments would ensure that enforcement officers had similar investigative powers to those being provided to Customs officers. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>In line with the recommendation that the power to obtain a production order be extended to an enforcement officer, we recommend that provisions dealing with the availability of the privilege against self-incrimination, and of certain other privileges that could be asserted in a criminal proceeding under the Evidence Act 2006, also be included in respect of the new power conferred on enforcement officers under new sections 134WA to 134WD. This would be achieved by the insertion of new section 134XA (which deals with the availability of the privilege of self-incrimination) and the proposed amendments to section 134Y. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Disposal of things seized</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending clauses 17 and 31 to align new section 134(V)(1) to the general provisions in sections 128 of the Trade Marks Act and sections 134 and 202 of the Copyright Act concerning the disposal of infringing items and objects. Our recommended amendment would ensure that a thing or object that had been seized was forfeited to the trade mark owner or the copyright owner, not to the Crown.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the insertion of new subclause 134V(1A) to align the provisions concerning the disposal of things seized more closely with the general provisions in the Trade Marks Act and the Copyright Act. Our recommendation would ensure that the Court took account of the need to ensure that no infringing goods or infringing copies were disposed of in a way that would adversely affect the owner of the registered trade mark or copyright. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Provisions concerning protection against infringement </heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the insertion of new clause 13A to clarify section 96(1) of the Trade Marks Act, which provides for no infringement for certain continuous use of an unregistered trademark. We recommend that section 96(1) of the Trade Marks Act be amended by repealing paragraph (b) and substituting new paragraphs (b) and (c). These amendments would ensure that, for the purpose of determining whether the owner of unregistered trade mark B has protection under this provision, the owner of registered trade mark A would not lose the right to rely on first use of trade mark A by a predecessor in title. They would also avoid any doubt that the owner of trade mark B could rely on prior use by the owner’s predecessors in title, but there must be continuous use of trade mark B by those predecessors in title and the current owner.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend that clause 13 be amended to ensure that the scope of protection from infringement given by section 95(b) is limited to where the use of the trade mark is “reasonably necessary” to indicate the intended purpose of goods or services. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Commissioner of Trade Marks</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that new clause 22 be deleted and new clause 22A inserted, inserting new sections 175 to 175C. These sections provide for the appointment of a Commissioner of Trade Marks and Assistant Commissioners of Trade Marks, the functions and power of delegation of the Commissioner, and the functions of the Assistant Commissioners. New clause 22A would bring the provisions concerning the appointment and powers of the Commissioner of Trade Marks and Assistant Commissioners of Trade Marks into closer alignment with the equivalent provisions in the Patents Bill 2008 concerning the Commissioner and Assistant Commissioners of Patents. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Alteration of register</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Clause 26 amends the Trade Mark Regulations 2003. We recommend amending clause 26 to substitute a new regulation 135 and to amend regulation 137. These provisions deal with procedural matters concerning alterations to the trade marks register. The changes recommended are to take account of the repeal, by clause 12(1), of the sections of the Act providing for the registration of licensees of trade marks, and the revocation of all such registrations by clause 12(2). </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Definition of trade mark</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that clause 4 be amended to insert new subclause 7(A), which amends the definition of trade mark in section 5(1). This would remove from the definition of a “trade mark” references to sections 83, 84, 86, and 87 concerning the registration of licensees that are repealed by clause 12.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Other amendments</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that clause 12(2), which revokes all registrations of licensees of trade marks, be amended to clarify that the revocation would apply also to registrations made under the Trade Marks Act 1953.  </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the insertion of new clause 18A, which repeals and substitutes new section 136, to clarify when the border protection measures would not apply to parallel-imported goods.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amendment to clause 21 (section 155A of the Trade Marks Act) and clause 35 (section 144 of the Copyright Act) to align the powers of Customs officers to seize infringing goods being imported with the criminal offences that apply to importing infringing goods under the Trade Marks Act and infringing copies, illicit recordings and TPM (Technological Protection Measure) circumvention devices under the Copyright Act.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Transitional provisions</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that clause 40 be omitted as it is no longer required as the Copyright (New Technologies) Act 2008 came into force on 31 October 2008. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Trade Marks (International Treaties and Enforcement) Amendment Bill was referred to the committee on 7 April 2009. The closing date for submissions was 15 May 2009. We received and considered 11 submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard two submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Ministry of Economic Development. The Regulations Review Committee reported to the committee on the powers contained in clauses 2(2) and 25.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>John Hayes (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Chris Carter</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Jacqui Dean</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hone Harawira (Non-voting member from 17 June 2009)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Pete Hodgson</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Dr Paul Hutchison</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Keith Locke</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Todd McClay</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Maryan Street</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.appendix>
    </commentary>
  </billdetail>
